defs.name: print

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new printer.

defs.name: print
defs.value: fn <W> (&mut self, ast: &Ast, wtr: W) -> fmt::Result
defs.docs:
Print the given `Ast` to the given writer. The writer must implement
 `fmt::Write`. Typical implementations of `fmt::Write` that can be used
 here are a `fmt::Formatter` (which is available in `fmt::Display`
 implementations) or a `&mut String`.

defs.name: Visitor
defs.docs: A trait for visiting an abstract syntax tree (AST) in depth first order.

defs.name: Output
defs.docs: The result of visiting an AST.

defs.name: Err
defs.docs: An error that visiting an AST might return.

defs.name: finish
defs.docs:
All implementors of `Visitor` must provide a `finish` method, which
 yields the result of visiting the AST or an error.

defs.name: start
defs.docs: This method is called before beginning traversal of the AST.

defs.name: visit_pre
defs.docs:
This method is called on an `Ast` before descending into child `Ast`
 nodes.

defs.name: visit_post
defs.docs:
This method is called on an `Ast` after descending all of its child
 `Ast` nodes.

defs.name: visit_alternation_in
defs.docs:
This method is called between child nodes of an
 [`Alternation`](struct.Alternation.html).

defs.name: visit_class_set_item_pre
defs.docs:
This method is called on every
 [`ClassSetItem`](enum.ClassSetItem.html)
 before descending into child nodes.

defs.name: visit_class_set_item_post
defs.docs:
This method is called on every
 [`ClassSetItem`](enum.ClassSetItem.html)
 after descending into child nodes.

defs.name: visit_class_set_binary_op_pre
defs.docs:
This method is called on every
 [`ClassSetBinaryOp`](struct.ClassSetBinaryOp.html)
 before descending into child nodes.

defs.name: visit_class_set_binary_op_post
defs.docs:
This method is called on every
 [`ClassSetBinaryOp`](struct.ClassSetBinaryOp.html)
 after descending into child nodes.

defs.name: visit_class_set_binary_op_in
defs.docs:
This method is called between the left hand and right hand child nodes
 of a [`ClassSetBinaryOp`](struct.ClassSetBinaryOp.html).

defs.name: visit
defs.docs: Executes an implementation of `Visitor` in constant stack space.

defs.name: Error
defs.docs:
An error that occurred while parsing a regular expression into an abstract
 syntax tree.

defs.name: kind
defs.docs: Return the type of this error.

defs.name: pattern
defs.docs: The original pattern string in which this error occurred.

defs.name: span
defs.docs: Return the span at which this error occurred.

defs.name: auxiliary_span
defs.docs:
Return an auxiliary span. This span exists only for some errors that
 benefit from being able to point to two locations in the original
 regular expression. For example, "duplicate" errors will have the
 main error position set to the duplicate occurrence while its
 auxiliary span will be set to the initial occurrence.

defs.name: CaptureLimitExceeded
defs.docs: The capturing group limit was exceeded.

defs.name: ClassEscapeInvalid
defs.docs: An invalid escape sequence was found in a character class set.

defs.name: ClassRangeInvalid
defs.docs:
An invalid character class range was found. An invalid range is any
 range where the start is greater than the end.

defs.name: ClassRangeLiteral
defs.docs:
An invalid range boundary was found in a character class. Range
 boundaries must be a single literal codepoint, but this error indicates
 that something else was found, such as a nested class.

defs.name: ClassUnclosed
defs.docs: An opening `[` was found with no corresponding closing `]`.

defs.name: DecimalEmpty
defs.docs:
Note that this error variant is no longer used. Namely, a decimal
 number can only appear as a repetition quantifier. When the number
 in a repetition quantifier is empty, then it gets its own specialized
 error, `RepetitionCountDecimalEmpty`.

defs.name: DecimalInvalid
defs.docs: An invalid decimal number was given where one was expected.

defs.name: EscapeHexEmpty
defs.docs: A bracketed hex literal was empty.

defs.name: EscapeHexInvalid
defs.docs: A bracketed hex literal did not correspond to a Unicode scalar value.

defs.name: EscapeHexInvalidDigit
defs.docs: An invalid hexadecimal digit was found.

defs.name: EscapeUnexpectedEof
defs.docs: EOF was found before an escape sequence was completed.

defs.name: EscapeUnrecognized
defs.docs: An unrecognized escape sequence.

defs.name: FlagDanglingNegation
defs.docs: A dangling negation was used when setting flags, e.g., `i-`.

defs.name: FlagDuplicate
defs.docs: A flag was used twice, e.g., `i-i`.

defs.name: FlagRepeatedNegation
defs.docs: The negation operator was used twice, e.g., `-i-s`.

defs.name: FlagUnexpectedEof
defs.docs: Expected a flag but got EOF, e.g., `(?`.

defs.name: FlagUnrecognized
defs.docs: Unrecognized flag, e.g., `a`.

defs.name: GroupNameDuplicate
defs.docs: A duplicate capture name was found.

defs.name: GroupNameEmpty
defs.docs: A capture group name is empty, e.g., `(?P<>abc)`.

defs.name: GroupNameInvalid
defs.docs:
An invalid character was seen for a capture group name. This includes
 errors where the first character is a digit (even though subsequent
 characters are allowed to be digits).

defs.name: GroupNameUnexpectedEof
defs.docs: A closing `>` could not be found for a capture group name.

defs.name: GroupUnclosed
defs.docs: An unclosed group, e.g., `(ab`.

defs.name: GroupUnopened
defs.docs: An unopened group, e.g., `ab)`.

defs.name: NestLimitExceeded
defs.docs:
The nest limit was exceeded. The limit stored here is the limit
 configured in the parser.

defs.name: RepetitionCountInvalid
defs.docs:
The range provided in a counted repetition operator is invalid. The
 range is invalid if the start is greater than the end.

defs.name: RepetitionCountDecimalEmpty
defs.docs:
An opening `{` was not followed by a valid decimal value.
 For example, `x{}` or `x{]}` would fail.

defs.name: RepetitionCountUnclosed
defs.docs: An opening `{` was found with no corresponding closing `}`.

defs.name: RepetitionMissing
defs.docs:
A repetition operator was applied to a missing sub-expression. This
 occurs, for example, in the regex consisting of just a `*` or even
 `(?i)*`. It is, however, possible to create a repetition operating on
 an empty sub-expression. For example, `()*` is still considered valid.

defs.name: UnicodeClassInvalid
defs.docs:
The Unicode class is not valid. This typically occurs when a `\p` is
 followed by something other than a `{`.

defs.name: UnsupportedBackreference
defs.docs:
When octal support is disabled, this error is produced when an octal
 escape is used. The octal escape is assumed to be an invocation of
 a backreference, which is the common case.

defs.name: UnsupportedLookAround
defs.docs:
When syntax similar to PCRE's look-around is used, this error is
 returned. Some example syntaxes that are rejected include, but are
 not necessarily limited to, `(?=re)`, `(?!re)`, `(?<=re)` and
 `(?<!re)`. Note that all of these syntaxes are otherwise invalid; this
 error is used to improve the user experience.

defs.name: __Nonexhaustive
defs.docs: Hints that destructuring should not be exhaustive.

defs.docs: The type of an error that occurred while building an AST.

defs.name: is_empty

Returns true if and only if this span is empty. That is, it points to
 a single position in the concrete syntax of a regular expression.

defs.name: Verbatim

defs.name: Punctuation

defs.name: Octal

defs.name: HexFixed
defs.docs:
The literal is written as a hex code with a fixed number of digits
 depending on the type of the escape, e.g., `\x61` or or `\u0061` or
 `\U00000061`.

defs.name: HexBrace
defs.docs:
The literal is written as a hex code with a bracketed number of
 digits. The only restriction is that the bracketed hex code must refer
 to a valid Unicode scalar value.

defs.name: Special
defs.docs:
The literal is written as a specially recognized escape, e.g., `\f`
 or `\n`.

defs.name: is_anchored_start
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if this HIR is required to match from the
 beginning of text. This includes expressions like `^foo`, `^(foo|bar)`,
 `^foo|^bar` but not `^foo|bar`.

defs.name: is_anchored_end
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if this HIR is required to match at the end
 of text. This includes expressions like `foo$`, `(foo|bar)$`,
 `foo$|bar$` but not `foo$|bar`.

defs.name: is_line_anchored_start
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if this HIR is required to match from the
 beginning of text or the beginning of a line. This includes expressions
 like `^foo`, `(?m)^foo`, `^(foo|bar)`, `^(foo|bar)`, `(?m)^foo|^bar`
 but not `^foo|bar` or `(?m)^foo|bar`.

defs.name: is_line_anchored_end
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if this HIR is required to match at the
 end of text or the end of a line. This includes expressions like
 `foo$`, `(?m)foo$`, `(foo|bar)$`, `(?m)(foo|bar)$`, `foo$|bar$`,
 `(?m)(foo|bar)$`, but not `foo$|bar` or `(?m)foo$|bar`.

defs.name: is_any_anchored_start
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if this HIR contains any sub-expression that
 is required to match at the beginning of text. Specifically, this
 returns true if the `^` symbol (when multiline mode is disabled) or the
 `\A` escape appear anywhere in the regex.

defs.name: is_any_anchored_end
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if this HIR contains any sub-expression that is
 required to match at the end of text. Specifically, this returns true
 if the `$` symbol (when multiline mode is disabled) or the `\z` escape
 appear anywhere in the regex.

defs.name: is_match_empty
defs.docs:

 matched by this regular expression.

defs.docs:

 true when this HIR expression is either itself a `Literal` or a
 concatenation of only `Literal`s.

defs.name: is_alternation_literal
defs.docs:
Return true if and only if this HIR is either a simple literal or an
 alternation of simple literals. This is only
 true when this HIR expression is either itself a `Literal` or a
 concatenation of only `Literal`s or an alternation of only `Literal`s.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Return true if and only if this HIR is the empty regular expression.

 empty) subexpressions.
